## Root Cause Analysis

### Issue 1: CSS Specificity -- Mobile `:hover` overrides `.pcl-active`

**The problem in detail:**

On line 280 of `ChapterReader.css`, inside the `@media (max-width: 768px)` block:

```css
.chapter-reader-content .editor-paragraph[data-paragraph-index]:hover {
    background-color: transparent;
}
```

This selector has specificity **0-4-0**: three class/attribute selectors (`.chapter-reader-content`, `.editor-paragraph`, `[data-paragraph-index]`) plus one pseudo-class (`:hover`).

The `.pcl-active` rule on line 269:

```css
.chapter-reader-content .editor-paragraph.pcl-active {
    background-color: var(--bg-selection);
}
```

This has specificity **0-3-0**: three class selectors (`.chapter-reader-content`, `.editor-paragraph`, `.pcl-active`).

On mobile browsers, a tap applies `:hover` state that persists. So when a user taps a paragraph, both rules match. The `:hover` transparent rule wins because 0-4-0 > 0-3-0. The highlight never appears.

**The fix:** Add the `[data-paragraph-index]` attribute selector to the `.pcl-active` rule to match specificity, then the source-order tie-break will favor `.pcl-active` (since it comes after the mobile `:hover` rule). Alternatively, place the `.pcl-active` rule **after** the mobile media query AND boost it to at least 0-4-0. The cleanest approach: move the `.pcl-active` rule after the mobile media query block and add the attribute selector.

The new rule becomes:

```css
.chapter-reader-content .editor-paragraph[data-paragraph-index].pcl-active {
    background-color: var(--bg-selection);
}
```

This has specificity **0-4-0** (same as the mobile `:hover` transparent rule), and since it appears later in source order, it wins. It also applies on all screen sizes, which is correct.

### Issue 2: `handleBadgeLeave` ignores `clickedRef`

On line 192-202 of `ParagraphCommentLayer.jsx`:

```javascript
const handleBadgeLeave = useCallback((idx, event) => {
    const nextTarget = event.relatedTarget;
    const nextParagraph = nextTarget?.closest?.('.editor-paragraph[data-paragraph-index]');
    if (nextParagraph && Number(nextParagraph.getAttribute('data-paragraph-index')) === idx) {
        return;
    }
    scheduleLeave(idx);  // <-- fires even when clickedRef.current is true
}, [scheduleLeave]);
```

The paragraph `leave` handler (line 80-93) correctly checks `if (clickedRef.current) return;` early. But `handleBadgeLeave` does not. So if a user clicks a paragraph (locking it via `clickedRef`), then their mouse passes over the badge and exits it, `handleBadgeLeave` will call `scheduleLeave(idx)`, which after 450ms clears `hoveredIndex` to `null`. This dismisses the highlight even though the user explicitly clicked.

**The fix:** Add `if (clickedRef.current) return;` as the first line of `handleBadgeLeave`.

```javascript
const handleBadgeLeave = useCallback((idx, event) => {
    if (clickedRef.current) return;

    const nextTarget = event.relatedTarget;
    // ... rest unchanged
}, [scheduleLeave]);
```

### Issue 3: Outside-click listener never registers after mouseenter-then-click

The outside-click effect on line 168-185:

```javascript
useEffect(() => {
    if (!clickedRef.current) return;
    // register document click listener ...
}, [hoveredIndex, containerRef]);
```

The dependency array is `[hoveredIndex, containerRef]`. This effect only re-runs when `hoveredIndex` changes. Here is the problematic sequence:

1. User hovers paragraph 3. `mouseenter` fires, calls `setHoveredIndex(3)`. React re-renders. The effect runs, but `clickedRef.current` is `false`, so it early-returns -- no listener registered.
2. User clicks paragraph 3. The click handler calls `clickedRef.current = true` and `setHoveredIndex(3)`. But `hoveredIndex` is already `3` -- React skips the re-render entirely. The effect does not re-run. The outside-click listener is never registered.
3. The user now cannot dismiss the highlight by clicking outside.

**The fix:** Introduce a state signal that forces the effect to re-run when a click happens, even if `hoveredIndex` doesn't change. The simplest approach is a counter state:

```javascript
const [clickSeq, setClickSeq] = useState(0);
```

In the paragraph click handler (line 94-98), increment it:

```javascript
const click = () => {
    clearLeaveTimer();
    clickedRef.current = true;
    setHoveredIndex(idx);
    setClickSeq(c => c + 1);
};
```

Then add `clickSeq` to the dependency array of the outside-click effect:

```javascript
useEffect(() => {
    if (!clickedRef.current) return;
    // register document click listener ...
}, [hoveredIndex, clickSeq, containerRef]);
```

Now, every click increments `clickSeq`, which guarantees the effect re-runs even when `hoveredIndex` is unchanged.

